Based on the required number of hosts, we determine how many bits to borrow for the network portion, ensuring an efficient use of the available address space.
By convention, the first usable address in each subnet is assigned to the network devices (e.g., PCs), while the last usable address is reserved for the routerâ€™s gateway interface.

ğŸ”¹ Step 1 â€” Subnet for 64 Hosts

The network with the highest number of hosts (64) is created first.
We borrow one additional bit for the network portion, resulting in a /25 subnet mask (255.255.255.128).

Network: 192.168.5.0/25

Host range: 192.168.5.1 â€“ 192.168.5.126

Broadcast: 192.168.5.127

Default gateway: 192.168.5.126

Example host: 192.168.5.1

ğŸ”¹ Step 2 â€” Subnet for 45 Hosts

Next, we create a subnet for 45 hosts.
Starting from the next available address (192.168.5.128), we apply a /26 mask (255.255.255.192), which provides 62 usable host addresses.

Network: 192.168.5.128/26

Host range: 192.168.5.129 â€“ 192.168.5.190

Broadcast: 192.168.5.191

Default gateway: 192.168.5.190

Example host: 192.168.5.129

ğŸ”¹ Step 3 â€” Subnet for 14 Hosts

The third network requires 14 hosts.
Since growth is not expected, we can use a /28 subnet mask (255.255.255.240), which provides exactly 14 usable addresses.

Network: 192.168.5.192/28

Host range: 192.168.5.193 â€“ 192.168.5.206

Broadcast: 192.168.5.207

Default gateway: 192.168.5.206

Example host: 192.168.5.193

ğŸ”¹ Step 4 â€” Subnet for Another 14 Hosts

We apply the same /28 mask (255.255.255.240) to the next subnet.

Network: 192.168.5.208/28

Host range: 192.168.5.209 â€“ 192.168.5.222

Broadcast: 192.168.5.223

Default gateway: 192.168.5.222

Example host: 192.168.5.209

ğŸ”¹ Step 5 â€” Point-to-Point Connection

For the router-to-router connection, only two IP addresses are required.
A /30 mask (255.255.255.252) is ideal since it provides two usable host addresses.

Network: 192.168.5.224/30

IP 1 (Router 1 interface): 192.168.5.225

IP 2 (Router 2 interface): 192.168.5.226

Broadcast: 192.168.5.227

âš™ï¸ Static Routing Configuration

Finally, static routing is configured so that packets can be forwarded between all subnets.

Example (on Router 1):

ip route 192.168.5.192 255.255.255.240 192.168.5.226


This route allows Router 1 to reach the 192.168.5.192/28 network via the point-to-point interface connected to Router 2.
